      "message": "Issue #1: Backwards Parameter Logic - Test Names Don\u0027t Match Behavior\n```\n# Test case at line 283\nDisable Admin User Verify User Is Not Allowed To Do SSH On SOL Port\n    Verify User Enable Disable And SSH Login  admin_user  Administrator  ${HOST_SOL_PORT}  ${False}\n\n# This calls the ELSE branch which ENABLES user first, then disables\n# But the test name says \"Disable Admin User\"\n```\n\nFix Required: The ${user_state} parameter is confusing. It should represent what action to test, not which branch to execute. Rename and refactor:\n\n```\n# Option 1: Rename parameter to match actual behavior\nVerify User Enable Disable And SSH Login\n    [Arguments]  ${username}  ${role}  ${port}  ${test_enable_flow}\n    # test_enable_flow\u003dTrue: test enabling (disable→enable)\n    # test_enable_flow\u003dFalse: test disabling (enable→disable)\n\n# Option 2: Separate into two keywords\nVerify User Disable Blocks SSH Access\n    [Arguments]  ${username}  ${role}  ${port}\n    Set User Account State  ${username}  ${True}\n    Verify SSH Login Access  ${username}  ${port}  ${True}\n    Set User Account State  ${username}  ${False}\n    Verify SSH Login Access  ${username}  ${port}  ${False}\n\nVerify User Enable Allows SSH Access\n    [Arguments]  ${username}  ${role}  ${port}\n    Set User Account State  ${username}  ${False}\n    Verify SSH Login Access  ${username}  ${port}  ${False}\n    Set User Account State  ${username}  ${True}\n    Verify SSH Login Access  ${username}  ${port}  ${True}\n```\n\nWhy: Current logic is backwards - test names don\u0027t match what the code actually does. This will cause confusion during maintenance and debugging. The \"Disable\" test actually starts by enabling the user, and vice versa.",
